“The sea is ours”: Bolivia’s landlocked hope that the court will reopen the way to the Pacific
The sailors are constantly patrolling the sea headquarters in La Paz.
There is an ocean blue flag flying over public buildings.
Marine bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are adorned with the motto: “The sea belongs to us by right.
It is our duty to take it back.”
In all of Bolivia, which has no access to the ocean, the memory of the lost outlet handed down to Chile after a bloody conflict in the 19th century is still alive - as is the call to sail the Pacific again.
In fact, this hope is currently the strongest in decades, while Bolivia awaits a ruling by the international court on October 1, after five years of deliberation.
"The power is in Bolivia, everywhere there is a sense of serenity and unity, and the country expects a positive result," Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzadilla said.
Many Bolivians will watch the ruling of the international court on the big screen across the country, hoping that the tribunal in The Hague will support Bolivia's claim and that after decades of negotiations Chile will be obliged to give Bolivia sovereign access to the ocean.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic local president facing a contentious re-election battle next year, has also staked much and much on the court’s judgment on Monday.
“We are very close to regaining access to the Pacific,” Morales promised last August.
But some analysts believe that the probability of the court ruling in Bolivia's favor is quite small. And even if it ruled in its favor, it would not change things into reality.
The Netherlands-based UN body does not have the authority to take over the territory of Chile and has ruled that it will not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
The fact that the ruling of the international court is only six months after the hearing of the last arguments indicates that the case is "not complicated," said Paz Zarate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And instead of contributing to Bolivia's cause, the last four years may have actually harmed it.
“The problem of access to the ocean has been exacerbated by the current government of Bolivia,” Zarate said.
He then hinted that Morales' belligerent rhetoric had wiped out what little good will remained of Chile.
Bolivia and Chile will continue negotiations at some point, but it will be extremely difficult after what happened to conduct a normal dialogue.
The two countries have not held diplomatic missions with each other since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodriguez Veltse, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision was taken unusually quickly.
On Monday, Bolivia will have the "incredible opportunity to open the page of a new era in its relations with Chile" and the chance to "end 139 years of disagreement by achieving benefit for both sides".
Kalzadila also rejected the idea that Morales - who continues to be one of the most popular presidents in Latin America - had used the ocean access problem as a "political crutch".
“Bolivia will never give up its right to leave the Pacific,” he added.
“Judgment is an opportunity to see that we have to overcome our past problems.”
