John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a reputation for academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another superb performance of exam scores, which was only reinforced by individual and collective successes in sports disciplines, art, music and other social sciences.
With up to 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Association of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to offer the best level to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for their further education, their chosen career and their place in a global world.
As an educational sector that can draw up and implement a personal curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desired subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you talk to someone in a language they understand, your words reach them.
But if you speak in his own language, you touch his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely solely on the English language when we want to build relationships and trust with the peoples of other countries.
With the results of this year’s exams, we see that languages are the first with the highest success rate for independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved the high grade A.
The data, which was collected from 74 members of SCIS schools, showed that 72% of students achieved a grade of A in Chinese, with the same grade having 72% of the German, 69% of the French and 63% of those with Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland perceive foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will definitely need in the future.
Currently, languages as a subject of free choice by students receive the same treatment as natural-mathematical disciplines (scientific, technological, engineering and mathematical disciplines) both in the programs of independent schools and beyond.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission showed that of the reasons employers struggle to find employees, 17% indicated insufficient language competences.
As a result, foreign language proficiency is becoming increasingly mandatory to prepare young people for their future careers.
More and more job positions require foreign language proficiency, making these skills essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the chosen career, if a person learns a foreign language, he will have a real advantage in the future, having mastered such a skill that remains for life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts the multilingual person one breast ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to be able to hold a language, with French being the only language whose proficiency reaches a double-digit percentage with an indicator of 15%.
This is why investing in language learning is important for children today.
Knowledge of several languages, especially those of developing economies, will provide children with a better chance of finding a good job.
In Scotland, every school will differ in terms of languages taught.
A number of schools will focus on more classic modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered more important to the UK in the future by 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever interests your child may have, there will always be enough languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers being specialists in their field.
Independent schools in Scotland are determined to provide an educational environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed in life, no matter what the future holds.
At the moment, it cannot be denied that in a global business environment, languages continue to play an incredibly important role in the future of any country, which requires this to be taken into account in the education system.
And indeed, modern languages should actually be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, along with diversity and excellent quality, to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Association of Independent Schools.
