North Korea says 'no way' to disarm unilaterally, without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were deepening distrust of the United States and there was no way the country could give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally in such circumstances.
At the UN's annual general assembly, Ri Yong-hou said "significant measures of goodwill" had been taken over the past year, for example halting nuclear and missile tests, destroying the nuclear test site, and promising not to spread nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see a corresponding reaction from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, we will not believe in our own national security and under no circumstances will we be the first to disarm unilaterally.”
While Ri expressed North Korea's familiar grievances about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to eliminating nuclear weapons, in which North Korea would be rewarded for taking staged measures, his statement seemed significant as it did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang did in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the U.S. president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work for "nuclear disarmament on the Korean peninsula" and Trump gave guarantees of North Korea's security.
North Korea sought an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the U.S. said Pyongyang should first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on ‘abolishing nuclear weapons first’ and increasing pressure through sanctions to achieve their goal through coercion, and even objects to the ‘declaration of the end of the war,’” Ri said.
“The notion that sanctions can get us down on our knees is a meaningless dream for those who don’t know us.
The problem, however, is that the continued sanctions are exacerbating our mistrust."
Ri did not mention whether a second meeting between Kim and Trump is planned, about which the US leader stressed at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister focused on three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the country on the issue of nuclear disarmament was South Korea and not the United States, the elimination of nuclear weapons on the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a standstill.
However, the tone of Ri's speech was significantly different from the previous year when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korean missiles at the U.S. mainland was inevitable after the "evil president" Trump called Kim a "man-missile" on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who threatened North Korea with "total destruction" last year, praised Kim for his courage to take disarmament measures, but said there was still a lot of work to be done and sanctions should remain in place until North Korea removes nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump said: “It doesn’t matter if it takes two years, three years or five months.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that: "The implementation of the Security Council sanctions must necessarily continue until full, final, and confirmed nuclear disarmament has taken place."
The Security Council has unanimously strengthened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in a bid to stop funding Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip went well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, but after just a few hours, North Korea accused him of making "gangster demands".
In a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to destroy a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States takes "appropriate measures".
He said Kim had told him that the "appropriate measures" he was seeking were the security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore and that he wanted to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students take enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year causes all students to sleep more in an attempt to combat the growing culture of learning "all night" using caffeine.
A professor found that students at the world’s number one university often don’t even think about it when it comes to the very basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Eisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, has prepared the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“Finally a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why are they telling me this now, in my senior year?’
She said that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, held for the first time this year, explains to students the most essentials of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after it was found that students suffered from a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a dorm room where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers, and books to explain to them the effects of caffeine and light, how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, and the importance of a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants were told how long-term sleep deprivation could increase the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Then a campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke."
The culture of pride in "all-night learning" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Ensuring adequate and quality sleep should be the students' "secret weapon" in combating stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he says - even in order to avoid weight gain, as sleep deprivation brings the brain into a starvation mode, causing them to be constantly hungry.
Raymond Soe, a 19-year-old student from California who studied chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Kaiser prepare the course by taking one of his classes in his first year at Harvard.
He says his course "opened his eyes" and inspired him to spread it throughout campus.
It is hoped that the next step is for all graduates to be asked to complete a similar curriculum before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Kaiser recommends that students think about whether to set a bedtime and wake-up alarm and know the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can upset the circadian rhythm and lead to sleep problems.
