Bernard Van: in memory of the priest awarded the Victoria Cross in the First World War
It marks 100 years in the hometown of the only Anglican priest to be awarded the Victoria Cross for his involvement in World War I.
Lieutenant-Colonel Bernard Van won the award on 29 September 1918 in the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
Four days later, however, he was killed by a sniper, unaware that he had been awarded Britain's highest military honours.
A commemorative monument was unveiled on Saturday by his two grandchildren, at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of his grandchildren, Michael Van, said it was "extremely symbolic" for the monument to be discovered exactly 100 years after his grandfather's medal-winning work.
According to the London Gazette on 29 September 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Van led his battalion through the Canal de Saint-Quentin "in very thick fog and under heavy fire from artillery and machine guns."
He later attacked the firing line and with "incredible bravery" led the line forward before attacking an artillery gun with one hand and killing three of the squad.
Lt. Col. Van was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just a month before the end of the war.
Michael Van, 72, said his grandfather's actions were "something I know I could never do, but it makes me humble."
He and his brother Dr. James Van laid a wreath after the parade, led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
