Germany postpones launch of new warship
The German Navy's newest frigate was due to be commissioned in 2014 to replace obsolete Cold War-era warships, but it won't happen until at least next year due to faulty systems and skyrocketing costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of "Rheinland-Pfalz", the brand's flagship new frigates of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class, was postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, which quoted an army spokesman.
The vessel was due to join the Navy in 2014, but the problems that arose after its delivery affected the fate of the ambitious project.
The four ships of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class, ordered by the fleet in 2007, will replace the obsolete Bremen-class frigates.
It is understood that they will have a powerful cannon, a set of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some stealth technologies, e.g. reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signals.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods - the latest frigates should be able to be used for up to two years before returning to ports of habitation.
Continuous delays, however, mean that advanced warships - rumored to allow Germany to demonstrate power overseas - will be old by the time they enter service, Die Zeit notes.
The ill-fated frigate F125 made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to put the vessel into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the Navy has returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but German media cited a number of substantial "software and hardware defects" that made the warship unusable if sent on a combat mission.
Software deficiencies are particularly important as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels will be manned by a crew of around 120 sailors - only half of the crew of the older Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, it turned out that the ship was significantly overloaded, which reduced its efficiency and limited the ability of the Navy to add future upgrades.
The 7000-ton "Rheinland-Pfalz" is thought to be twice as heavy as the ships of a similar class used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to faulty hardware, the cost of the entire project - including crew training - is also becoming a problem.
It is estimated to have reached a staggering 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion), up from the original 2.2 billion euros.
Problems with the latest frigates have become particularly important in light of recent warnings that Germany's naval forces are shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defense committee, admitted that the navy was in fact "exhausted from ships capable of carrying out missions."
The official said the problem had become bigger over time as the old ships were decommissioned, but no new ones were provided.
He complained that no Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates could join the fleet.
The National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
A new study conducted at a mansion in the Scottish Highlands aims to find out how bats use the landscape when hunting.
Hopes are that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation actions.
The study by scientists from the National Trust of Scotland will follow common bats as well as brown arrow-eared water moths at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations at the estate to track bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the call sounds of bats, as well as which species issue them.
A habitat map and a report will then be drawn up to create a detailed landscape picture of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, e.g. creating meadows, as well as the best way to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the UK as a whole have declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction activities that affect their shelters and lead to habitat loss.
Risk to populations may be from wind turbines and lighting, aircraft, and some chemical processing of building materials, as well as attacks from domestic cats.
In reality, bats are not blind.
However, due to their hunting habits at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation techniques to detect insects and obstacles along their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens of great importance and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The Trust has trained experts who conduct regular surveys, asylum inspections and sometimes rescue operations.
The organisation has even created the first in Scotland and the only special reserve for bats in the Threeve estate in the Dumfries and Galloway area, which is home to eight of the ten bat species in Scotland.
The manor's manager, David Thompson, says it's an ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threeve, we have great terrain for bats," he noted.
“We have old buildings, many old trees, and a suitable habitat completed.
But there's a lot more to bats that aren't known, so the work we do here and at other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive."
He stressed that it is important to check for the presence of bats before carrying out property maintenance activities, as it is possible the unintentional destruction of one asylum to kill up to 400 female and young bats, as well as to destroy an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their shelters.
Elizabeth Farrell, a Scottish official at the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said, "I still have a lot to learn about our bats and many of our animal species, because we just don't know what's going on with their populations."
