New for the red tide: Concentrations decline in Pinellas, Manotti and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Committee shows a general decrease in red tide concentrations in sections of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Committee, there have been reports of growth disruption in the areas of Pinellas, Manutti, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties - this indicates a decrease in concentrations.
The watersheds with excessive red tide blooms extend for approximately 130 miles along the coast, from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
Algae patches can be seen 10 miles off the coast of Hillsboro County, but are smaller than last week.
Red tide is also observed in Pasco County.
In the past week, there have been reports of moderate concentrations in the coastal zone or slightly further inland in Pinellas County, low to high concentrations along the coast of Hillsboro County, prerequisites for high concentrations in Manotti County, prerequisites for high concentrations in the coast or further inland in Sarasota County, prerequisites for moderate concentrations in Charlotte County, both prerequisites for high concentrations in the coast and along the coast.
Inflammation of the airways in Pinellas, Manotti, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties continued to be reported.
There have been no reports of respiratory infections in Northwest Florida in the past week.
